Libraries worldwide that own item: 1 Search the HOLLIS CatalogExternal Resources:  Cite This ItemFind Items About:    Gardner, Alan Gardner,max: 21Title:                Letter from Lord Gardner, Admirals Penn, to an unidentified recipient, 1787 May 28 :autograph manuscript signed.Author(s):           Gardner, Alan Gardner, Baron, 1742-1809.Publication:         Kingston, Jamaica,Place:               Jamaica; Kingston.Year:                1787-05-28Description:         1 item (2 pages) ; 24.1 x 19.0 cmLanguage:            EnglishStandard No:         Other:               MA 23039.1Abstract:            Concerning the arrival of Prince William Henry aboard the Pegasus; saying "I have communicated to His Royal Highness Prince William Henry the purport of your letter of yesterdayand of your inventions of ordering the Forts and Batteries to pay the compliment due to His exalted Station on His landing from His Ship to-morrow ; in reply, His Royal Highness inform'd me, thatMajor Amherst had waited upon Him on board the Pegasus by your direction, and that He had signified his pleasure to the Major respecting these matters, which Major Amherst of course has fullycommunicated to you. His Royal Highness has not as yet fix'd upon any day for visiting you at the Kings House, or I most certainly should have given you notice of it, on His arrival I made His RoyalHighness an offer of a Bed at the Adm'ls Penn, which He declined, assuring me that it was a rule with Him never to sleep out of His Ship."SUBJECT(S)Descriptor:          1787 05 28.Named Person:        William IV, King of Great Britain, 1765-1837.William IV, King of Great Britain, 1765-1837.Note(s):             Housed with a letter from Lord Gardner to Messrs Parker & Sons (MA 23039.2)/ Bio/History:         Officer in the British Royal Navy.Material Type:       Manuscript (mss)Document Type:       Book; Archival MaterialDate of Entry:       19990323Update:              20220719Accession No:        OCLC:                269563402Provider:        OCLCDatabase:            WorldCat--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Both were 300 ton copper sheathedsingle-deckers that plied the West Indies trade route during the 1780s./ Bio/History:            Captain James Henderson of the ship 'Industry' replaced Captain William Mattocks of the 'Triton' whenthe latter became captain of the newly built 'Sybil' in 1782. Henderson then became captain of the 'Sybil' in 1786 after Mattocks died at sea. Captain Thomas Powell served on the 'Druid' (built in1777) from 1782-1788 at least (replacing Captain Stott in 1782). These ships were part of the shipping concern of Lowbridge & Richard Bright of Bristol, which specifically focused on trade to Jamaica.Class Descriptors:       LC: HE825Material Type:          Manuscript (mss)Document Type:          Book; Archival MaterialDate of Entry:          20180726Update:                 20220321Accession No:           OCLC:                   1046079858Provider:        OCLCDatabase:               WorldCat--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

column11: The printing of the volumes and project was organized by Bryan Edwards./ Alexander Aikman was printing in Spanish Town, Jamaica in 1795, 1797, 1798, 1800, 1802, 1804, 1805,1807, 1809, and 1816./ Alexander Aikman junior was printing in Kingston in 1822./ Imprint of vol. 13 reads: By Alexander Aikman, junior, Jamaica. Printer to the honourable House of Assembly, 1822;Imprint of vol. 14 reads: By Alexander Aikman, junior, Jamaica. Printer to the honourable House of Assembly, 1826./ Volume 1 printed in 1811; volume 2 printed in 1795; volume 3 printed in 1797;volume 4 printed in 1797; volume 5 printed in 1798; volume 6 printed in 1800; volume 7 printed in 1802; volume 8 printed in 1804; volume 9 printed in 1805; volume 10 printed in 1807; volume 11printed in 1809; volume 12 printed in 1816; v. 13 printed in 1822; v. 14 printed in 1829./ According to the notes in the preface to volume 1, dated 1811, when the House ordered the printing of theJournals, it was discovered that a number of the earlier notes and minutes were missing or damaged: "Therefore, publication began with the second volume..1709-1710 ... and continued successively tothe 11th, ending with the session in 1807, whilst inquiries and researches were made in Great Britain for copies of the minutes that had been destroyed."/ All volumes printed entirely on wove paper./"Appendix to the first volume of the Journals of the Assembly of Jamaica", v. 1, p. [3-6] and [1]-53, 5th and 6th counts, has divisional title page./ Indexes appear following Journal in each volume./The several indexes (printed 1803-1829) are sometimes found bound separately as a fifteenth volume. Libraries worldwide that own item: 1 Search the HOLLIS CatalogExternal Resources:  Cite This ItemFind Items About:    Frazer, William19Title:                [Jamaica diary].Author(s):           Frazer, William (Surveyor)Publication:         [Jamaica],Place:               Jamaica.Year:                1797-1805Description:         [158] p. ; 16 x 21 cm. (4to)Language:            EnglishSUBJECT(S)Descriptor:          Surveyors -- Jamaica.Surveying -- Jamaica.Manuscripts -- Jamaica.Manuscripts -- English.Géomètres -- Jamaïque.Manuscrits -- Jamaïque.Manuscripts.Surveying.Surveyors.Named Person:        Frazer, William (Surveyor) -- Diaries.Genre/Form:          Diaries.History.Geographic:          Jamaica -- History.Jamaïque -- Histoire.Jamaica.Identifier:          Imprint 1797.; Imprint 1805.Note(s):             Ms. codex./ Title supplied from spine label on phase box housing the diary./ Attributed to William Frazer, a surveyor in Jamaica, from internal evidence, handwritingcomparaisons, and other information by B.W. Higman, in his Jamaica surveyed: plantation maps and plans of the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, 1988./ Caption title on p. [1] reads: Sunday,January 1st, 1797./ Diary extends from January 1, 1797 until September 1, 1805, where the last entry on September 24th indicates that "the writer of this book died at St. Jago Farm [in ClarendonParish, Jamaica] at 9 o'clock P.M. and was buried at Ebony Grove at 5 o'clock P.M. this day. J. Rome"/ Mention is made in the diary of fellow surveyors John Fullarton and John Rome, Jr. The author isrecorded in Higman's book as having collaborated with both men, as well as working independently. Fraser was employed as surveyor on commission from 1787 until his death in 1805. This diary whollytakes place in Clarendon Parish, Jamaica, and is located in the south of the island, roughly half way between the island's eastern and western ends. Located in the county of Middlesex, it is borderedby Manchester on the west, Saint Catherine in the east, and in the north by Saint Ann./ The diary contains information for whom the author worked, on what he worked, where he dined and with whom, andwhere he slept. If he was not working, he recorded what illnesses he had and what remedies he was trying to clear those illnesses. There is a running column for the weather and another columnentitled "Remarks", in which he records deaths, births, marriages and unusual events./ Vertical chain lines./ Text in written in red and black ink with occasional illustration of cherubs orornamental borders in the author's hand on caption title pages.Class Descriptors:    Dewey: Codex; Eng; 217Other Titles:        Sunday, January 1st, 1797.Material Type:       Manuscript (mss)Document Type:       Book; Archival MaterialDate of Entry:       20110304Update:              20220628Accession No:        OCLC:                705372507Provider:        OCLCDatabase:            WorldCat--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Libraries worldwide that own item: 1 Search the HOLLIS CatalogExternal Resources:       Cite This ItemTitle:An excursion into the interior from the Cape of Good Hope.Publication:              [Jamaica?] : [publisher not identified],Place:                    Jamaica.Year:                     1799-1802?Description:              xix, [1], 126 pages, 4 unnumbered leaves of plates : illustrations ; 20 cmLanguage:                 EnglishSUBJECT(S)Descriptor:               Plants -- South Africa -- Cape of Good Hope.Plants -- Jamaica.Plants.Travel.Genre/Form:               Relief prints.Geographic:               Cape of Good Hope (South Africa) -- Description and travel.Le Cap (Afrique du Sud : Province) -- Descriptions et voyages.Jamaica.South Africa -- Cape of Good Hope.Note(s):                  Describing a (fictitious?) journey exploring the Cape Colony in late summer 1798, endorsing the British colonial presence and concluding that "it is greatly to be desiredthat the cession of the Cape, may never be allowed by a British ministry as a sine qua non of pacificatory negociation" (p. 94)./ Only recorded copy appears to lack title page; title from caption./Presumably printed between 1799, the latest watermark date, and 1802, when the British ceded the Cape Colony to the Batavian Republic as part of the Treaty of Amiens./ Error in paging: p. 61-68misnumbered 57-64./ "Botanical appendix," p. 103-125, lists "plants peculiar to the Cape of Good Hope" and marks those found in the botanical gardens at Linguanea, Jamaica. The "explanation of thecuts," "dedication," and "epistle to the reader" suggest that the anonymous author lived in Jamaica./ "Errata."--Page 125-126.Document Type:            BookEntry:                    20141105Update:                   20220507Accession No:             OCLC:                     908991758Provider:        OCLCDatabase:                 WorldCat--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

documentary items which include: (1) A proclamation of the Protector relating to Jamaica. --(2) A letter from Christopher Columbus in Jamaica to the king of Spain [1503].-- (3) A narrative by general Venables of his expedition to the island of Jamaica, and the conquest thereof under the protectorship of Oliver Cromwell. -- (4) Laws military for the island of Jamaica,published by his excellency Sir Thomas Modyford. -- (6) The present state of Jamaica, in a letter from Mr. Nevil to the Earl of Carlisle. -- (8) A report of the right honourable the lords of thecommittee for trade and plantations to the king at the Court of Whitehall the 28th of May, 1679. -- (9) An address of the assembly of Jamaica to the Earl of Carlisle. --(10) A proclamacon [sic] forthe encouraging of planters in his majesty's island of Jamaica, in the West-Indies. -- (12) An abstract of the government of Jamaica since his majesty's restoration, given in by Sir Thomas Lynch tothe king in council. -- (13) A petition of Samuel Long, esq. against the Earl of Carlisle, to the king in council, with the earl's answer thereto. -- (15) The Earl of Carlisle's answer to a chargeagainst him, exhibited to his majesty in council, by Samuel Long. -- (16) An account of some affairs in Jamaica during the government of the Earl of Carlisle. -- (17) A patent from King Charles IIfor the office of surveyor and auditor-general of the revenues in Jamaica. -- (18) A dialogue between two assembly-men of Jamaica, for and against passing the revenue bill for seven years. -- (20)The governor's speech to the assembly of Jamaica. -- (21) The king's instructions to Sir Philip Howard, knight. -- (25) South Sea account, by Arnold. -- (28) An address of the Catholics in Jamaica tothe Duke of Albemarle. -- (30) King William's instructions to the Earl of Inchiquin. -- 33. Autograph letter signed :Author(s):                Honyman, Robert, 1781-1808.Pulteney, James,; Sir,; approximately 1751-1811, ; recipient.Ouvry, Frederic,; 1814-1881, ; former owner.Ford, Gordon Lester,; 1823-1891, ; former owner.Ford, Worthington Chauncey,; 1858-1941, ; former owner.Ford, Paul Leicester,; 1865-1902, ; former owner.Place:                    Jamaica; Spanish Town.Year:                     1808-02-05Description:              1 item (7 pages) ; 22.9 cmIn:                       Pulteney Correspondence (MA 1265) item 25 boundLanguage:                 EnglishStandard No:              Other:                    MA 1265.25Abstract:                 Enclosing several Returns and reporting on the state of the Battalion under his command; reporting "we have a very great proportion of Sick, caused chiefly by the extremestate of weakness and debility to which the whole are reduced by severe and repeated Sickness, every man in the Reg't having been ... in Hospital at least three times during the last twelve months.It shall be my endeavour to nurse them as much as their exhausted State requires which however puts a final stop to any other attempt being made for their improvement. It is not perhaps for me tomake any further observations than those that merely fall under the Official communication of a Comm'g officer, yet Sir, it is impossible not to deplore the melancholy fate of so many young men, thatwould in any other Climate have done honor to their Country ... With regard to the Accoutrements they are certainly bad, yet I hope to be able to make them hold out while we remain in this Country;"asking for a set of Brass drums; reporting on the stores of clothing; discussing personnel issues concerning several officers; reporting, in a postscript, that they have insufficient DrummersClothing.SUBJECT(S)Descriptor:               1808 02 05.Note(s):                  Endorsed./ Volume 8 (MA 1265) of a 33-volume collection of the correspondence of Sir James Pulteney, his family and distinguished contemporaries. (MA 487, MA 297 and MA1260-1290). The arrangement of the collection is alphabetical by the author of the letter. Libraries worldwide that own item: 1 Search the HOLLIS CatalogExternal Resources:  Cite This ItemFind Items About:    Cheney, Ednah Dow,max: 65Baskin, Lisa Unger,9Sallie Bingham Center for Women's History and Culture.6Title:                Ednah Dow Cheney letter to Mrs. Parsons, 1897 November 22 :autograph manuscript signed.Author(s):           Cheney, Ednah Dow, 1824-1904,  correspondent.Baskin, Lisa Unger, ; former owner.Corp Author(s):      Lisa Unger Baskin Collection (David M. Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library) ; Sallie Bingham Center for Women's History and Culture.Publication:         Jamaica Plain, Boston, Massachusetts,Year:                1897Description:         1 item (1 leaf) : paper; 16 x 21 cm, folded to 16 x 11 cmLanguage:            English; In English.Abstract:            Cheney writes to Mrs. Parsons to accept materials to be sold to raise money for causes the two mutually support. She notes that she did not know the material had arrived becauseshe was unable to go to the suffrage rooms, and adds that Miss Blackwell will write notices about the pamphlets Parsons enclosed. Cheney states that she will attempt to sell the autographs at privatesale and that her hospital sales have been managed in the past by Eva Channing, who is in Europe. Written on her engraved Jamaica Plain stationary.SUBJECT(S)Descriptor:          Social movements -- United States -- History -- 19th century.Women political activists -- United States.Mouvements sociaux -- États-Unis -- Histoire -- 19e siècle.Femmes activistes -- États-Unis.Social movements.Women political activists.Named Person:        Cheney, Ednah Dow, 1824-1904.Cheney, Ednah Dow, 1824-1904.Genre/Form:          History.Time:                1800-1899Geographic:          United States.Note(s):             Title devised by cataloger./ Bio/History:         Ednah Dow Littlehale Cheney was a writer, reformer, and philanthropist. After her husband's death in 1856 she took an interestin social concerns such as the Freedman's Aid Society (secretary of the committee on aid for colored regiments and of the teachers' committee, 1863), Massachusetts Woman Suffrage Association (vicepresident), New England Women's Club (vice president) and the New England Hospital for Women and Children (secretary, 1862). She lectured at the Concord School of Philosophy on the history of art.She was an active member of the Margaret Fuller conversation class. She went south to visit the Freedmen's schools in 1866, 1868, and 1869. She visited Europe several times, and spoke before lyceumswest of New England in 1873, 1875, and 1876.General Info:        Collection is open for research./ The copyright interests in this collection have not been transferred to Duke University. column10: Descriptor: Social movements -- United States -- History -- 19th century.Women political activists -- United States.Mouvements sociaux -- États-Unis -- Histoire -- 19e siècle.Femmes activistes -- États-Unis.Social movements.Women political activists.Named Person: Cheney, Ednah Dow, 1824-1904.Cheney, Ednah Dow, 1824-1904.Genre/Form: History.Time: 1800-1899Geographic: United States.Note(s): Title devised by cataloger./ Bio/History: Ednah Dow Littlehale Cheney was a writer, reformer, and philanthropist. After her husband's death in 1856 she took an interestin social concerns such as the Freedman's Aid Society (secretary of the committee on aid for colored regiments and of the teachers' committee, 1863), Massachusetts Woman Suffrage Association (vicepresident), New England Women's Club (vice president) and the New England Hospital for Women and Children (secretary, 1862). She lectured at the Concord School of Philosophy on the history of art.She was an active member of the Margaret Fuller conversation
